Let $y=|2 \hat{a}-3 \hat{b}|^2+|2 \hat{b}-3 \hat{c}|^2+|2 \hat{c}-3 \hat{a}|^2$
$\begin{aligned}
& \Rightarrow \mathrm{y}=3(4+9)-12(\hat{\mathrm{a}} \cdot \hat{\mathrm{~b}}+\hat{\mathrm{b}} \cdot \hat{\mathrm{c}}+\hat{\mathrm{c}} \cdot \hat{\mathrm{a}}) \\
& \Rightarrow \mathrm{y}=39-12(\hat{\mathrm{a}} \cdot \hat{\mathrm{~b}}+\hat{\mathrm{b}} \cdot \hat{\mathrm{c}}+\hat{\mathrm{c}} \cdot \hat{\mathrm{a}}) \qquad ...(1)
\end{aligned}$
$\begin{aligned}
& {\left[\begin{array}{l}
\text { As }|\hat{a}+\hat{b}+\hat{c}|^2 \geq 0 \Rightarrow 3+2(\hat{a} \cdot \hat{b}+\hat{b} \cdot \hat{c}+\hat{c} \cdot \hat{a}) \geq 0 \\
\Rightarrow \hat{a} \cdot \hat{b}+\hat{b} \cdot \hat{c}+\hat{c} \cdot \hat{a} \geq \frac{-3}{2}
\end{array}\right]} \\
& \Rightarrow y_{\max }=39+(12)\left(\frac{3}{2}\right)=39+18=57 \text { Ans. }
\end{aligned}$
Now y will be maximum if value of $\sum \hat{\mathrm{a}} \cdot \hat{\mathrm{b}}$ is minimum i.e. equal to $-\frac{3}{2}$
